To create another instance of myButton in the Game constructor, you can add it to the initialization list with a different name. You'll need to first declare the second button as a member variable in your Game class header file, and then initialize it in the constructor like this:

```cpp
Game::Game() : 
    myButton("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69.png", 70, 680, screen_height),
    myButton2("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69.png", 170, 680, screen_height)  // New button
{
}
```

Make sure you've declared both buttons in your Game class header file (Game.h):
```cpp
class Game {
private:
    Button myButton;
    Button myButton2;  // Add this declaration
    // ... other members
};
```

The numbers 170, 680 in the second button represent different x, y coordinates to position the second button in a different location. You can adjust these values to place the button where you want it on the screen.
why does highlight the opening ccurly bracket here 
Game::Game() :
    myButton("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69.png", 70, 680, screen_height),
    myButtonRight("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69right.png", 140, 740, screen_height),
    myButtonDown("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69left.png", 10, 740, screen_height),
    {
}
The error occurs because there's an extra comma after the last initialization in the member initialization list. Remove the comma after `screen_height)` and it should work correctly:

```cpp
Game::Game() :
    myButton("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69.png", 70, 680, screen_height),
    myButtonRight("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69right.png", 140, 740, screen_height),
    myButtonDown("/Users/markbabin/CODE/C++/sprite69left.png", 10, 740, screen_height)  // Remove comma here
{
}
```

The member initialization list should have commas between initializations but not after the last one before the opening curly brace.
